"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147990","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-07","<p>The Government understands the concern about the cost of some rail fares and the impact that this can have on people’s budgets. This is why the Government has ensured that regulated rail fares can rise by no more than inflation for the last six years. The Williams Review is considering how to enable a railway that is able to offer good value fares for passengers, while keeping costs down for taxpayers.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-10-07T16:51:32.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147990/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147990/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147990/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-02","Railways: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department will review the cost of train fares.","false","Biography information for Sandy Martin","Ipswich","Sandy Martin","293736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147991","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-07","<p>DWP stands ready to support anyone affected by the closure of Thomas Cook, with our Rapid Response Service (RRS) offer. This is a redundancy service designed to give support and advice to employers and their employees when faced with redundancy. It is coordinated nationally by the National Employer and Partnership Team (NEPT) and is managed by Jobcentre Plus.</p><p> </p><p>The RRS has been mobilised to help people find a new job as soon as possible by offering tailored support. Each Jobcentre Plus district deploy resources according to the situation and the requirements of the workforce. The RRS is delivered in partnership with a range of national and local partners, including National Careers Service and local service providers.</p><p> </p><p>NEPT have contacted several large employers and trade bodies to identify a range of opportunities for Thomas Cook members of staff who have lost their jobs and the Department is working closely with over 100 employers to offer support and opportunities. We are delivering over 65 Job Fairs nationally, where ex-employees can meet local employers with vacancies.</p><p> </p><p>The full range of support available from Jobcentre Plus and partners includes:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Information advice and guidance.</li><li>Connecting people to jobs in the labour market.</li><li>Help with job search including CV writing, interview skills, where to find jobs and how to apply for them.</li><li>Help to identify transferable skills and skills gaps (linked to the local labour<br> market).</li><li>Training to update skills, learn new ones and gain industry recognised<br> certification that will improve employability.</li><li>Help to overcome barriers to attending training or securing a job or <br> self-employment such as child care costs, necessary tools, work clothes, travel costs etc.</li><li>On-site presentations to those affected.</li><li>Job Fairs and Job Clubs where appropriate.</li></ul><p> </p><p>Our local teams are monitoring all new claims to benefits to identify where the claimant is an ex-employee of Thomas Cook so that they quickly receive the right level of support.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested on the number of ex-employees who have been offered alternative employment opportunities is not available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","293717","2019-10-07T17:05:18.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147991/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147991/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-02","Thomas Cook: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what dedicated emergency support her Department has put in place to help and advise Thomas Cook members of staff who have lost their jobs.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","293716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147992","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-07","<p>DWP stands ready to support anyone affected by the closure of Thomas Cook, with our Rapid Response Service (RRS) offer. This is a redundancy service designed to give support and advice to employers and their employees when faced with redundancy. It is coordinated nationally by the National Employer and Partnership Team (NEPT) and is managed by Jobcentre Plus.</p><p> </p><p>The RRS has been mobilised to help people find a new job as soon as possible by offering tailored support. Each Jobcentre Plus district deploy resources according to the situation and the requirements of the workforce. The RRS is delivered in partnership with a range of national and local partners, including National Careers Service and local service providers.</p><p> </p><p>NEPT have contacted several large employers and trade bodies to identify a range of opportunities for Thomas Cook members of staff who have lost their jobs and the Department is working closely with over 100 employers to offer support and opportunities. We are delivering over 65 Job Fairs nationally, where ex-employees can meet local employers with vacancies.</p><p> </p><p>The full range of support available from Jobcentre Plus and partners includes:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Information advice and guidance.</li><li>Connecting people to jobs in the labour market.</li><li>Help with job search including CV writing, interview skills, where to find jobs and how to apply for them.</li><li>Help to identify transferable skills and skills gaps (linked to the local labour<br> market).</li><li>Training to update skills, learn new ones and gain industry recognised<br> certification that will improve employability.</li><li>Help to overcome barriers to attending training or securing a job or <br> self-employment such as child care costs, necessary tools, work clothes, travel costs etc.</li><li>On-site presentations to those affected.</li><li>Job Fairs and Job Clubs where appropriate.</li></ul><p> </p><p>Our local teams are monitoring all new claims to benefits to identify where the claimant is an ex-employee of Thomas Cook so that they quickly receive the right level of support.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested on the number of ex-employees who have been offered alternative employment opportunities is not available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","293716","2019-10-07T17:05:18.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147992/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147992/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-02","Thomas Cook: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many employees of Thomas Cook who have lost their jobs following the company's collapse have been offered alternative employment opportunities as of 2 October 2019.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","293717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147993","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-08","<p>Thomas Cook schemes provide both Defined Contribution and Defined Benefit pensions.</p><p> </p><p>Defined Contribution pensions are operated independently of Thomas Cook, with funds held separately. Pension pots will not be affected and will continue to be invested on behalf of the members. If there are unpaid pension contributions the Insolvency Service can make payments out of the National Insurance Fund within specified limits.</p><p> </p><p>The Thomas Cook Defined Benefit pension schemes are protected by the Pension Protection Fund. These schemes are well funded and are able to continue to paying out pensions to their members. The Pension Protection Fund will assess whether it will need to take responsibility for payments in the future. Payments cannot be lower than the level of Pension Protection Fund compensation – which is 100% of pension for those currently above the scheme retirement age, and 90% subject to a cap for those who are younger, but this may be higher.</p><p> </p><p>The trustees of the Defined Benefit pension schemes are in touch with members. The Pension Protection Fund has provided contact details if members have questions.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2019-10-08T13:29:50.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147993/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147993/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-02","Thomas Cook: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps she is taking to provide pension protection for Thomas Cook staff.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","293718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147994","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-10-08","<p>The Government regularly engages with UK retailers on a wide variety of policy areas, including on the sustainability of fish stocks in UK waters and beyond.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2019-10-08T12:04:41.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147994/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147994/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-02","Fish: Supermarkets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions his Department has had with representatives of supermarkets on the sale of endangered fish species.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","293476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147995","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-10-08","<p>The Solar photovoltaics deployment report, published on the gov.uk website, provides information on solar photovoltaic capacity in the United Kingdom. It currently includes solar installations reported in BEIS' major power producers survey, the Renewable Energy Planning Database, the Microgeneration Certification Scheme database, and those subsidised by the Renewables Obligation, Feed-in Tariff, and Contracts for Difference. It does not currently include unsubsidised solar installations below 1MW capacity that are not registered on the Microgeneration Certification Scheme database, although we are reviewing data sources to improve coverage.</p>","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng",,"2019-10-08T14:00:30.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147995/answer","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147995/answer","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147995/answer/previousversion/138025","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-10-02","Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that Ofgem is able to collate accurate data on the installation of solar power units.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","293680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147996","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-07","<p>The Department fully understands that maintaining access to hormone replacement therapy (HRT) medications is vitally important to many people in this country.</p><p>We are aware of ongoing supply issues with some HRT transdermal patches due to manufacturing issues. We have been working closely with all suppliers of HRT transdermal patches to maintain overall supply to patients. Although some HRT transdermal patches are affected by supply issues, supplies of other alternative HRT transdermal patches have remained available.</p>","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill",,"2019-10-07T16:53:50.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147996/answer","Biography information for Jo Churchill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147996/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-10-02","Hormone Replacement Therapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps the Department has taken to ensure that women who are unable to use alternative forms of HRT have access to HRT patches.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","293445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147997","Cabinet Office","false","2019-10-07","<p>The Government policy is that all workers in the UK are paid the statutory National Minimum Wage or National Living Wage. This is based on the advice of the Low Pay Commission. In April 2019, the National Living Wage increased to £8.21 per hour, handing a full-time worker a further £690 annual pay rise. By 2024 the National Living Wage will rise to £10.50 per hour, reaching 66% of median UK earnings. The scope will be expanded to everyone aged 21 and over and is expected to benefit over 4 million low paid workers.</p><p> </p>","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart",,"2019-10-07T14:22:29.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147997/answer","Biography information for Simon Hart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147997/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-10-02","Government Departments: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make it his policy to ensure that the London Living Wage is paid by all Government Departments and their contractors.","true","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","293677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147998","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-08","<p>Local welfare assistance is an umbrella term used describe local authority provision for people who are in need of urgent help. Local authorities’ abilities to act in this area are provided under various powers, for example, section 2 of the Local Government Act 2000 enables local authorities to provide financial assistance to any individual.</p><p> </p><p>Since the reforms to the Social Fund in 2013 which abolished Crisis Loans and Community Care Grants, the Local Government Financial Settlement has included a notional amount relating to local welfare provision in each upper-tier and unitary authority’s general grant. The settlement for 2015-16 set this amount at £129.6 million for England in each year until 2019/20.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Work and Pension's (DWP) 2014 review found that local authorities delivered support more effectively than the previous provision and that councils are best placed to decide how to target flexible help to support local welfare needs. The Government has no further plans to review provision.</p><p />","Colchester","Will Quince","293440","2019-10-08T13:21:57.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147998/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147998/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147998/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-10-02","Welfare Assistance Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether her Department has departmental responsibility for local welfare assistance schemes.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","293545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147999","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-10-08","<p>Responsibility for funding for local welfare provision was passed over from the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) to the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government (MHCLG) from April 2013. The MHCLG would lead on any changes in allocation with input from the DWP.</p>","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall",,"2019-10-08T14:12:34.48Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147999/answer","Biography information for Luke Hall","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147999/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147999/answer","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1147999/answer/previousversion/137981","Biography information for Luke Hall","7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-10-02","Welfare Assistance Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department is responsible for allocating funding for local welfare assistance schemes.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","293546"
